I use .NET Core to manage a child process. The child process reads one line at a time and prints corresponding output. The code looks like this:

```cs
Task.Run(async () =>
{
    foreach (string line in File.ReadAllLines("test_values_300.txt"))
    {
        await searchTableProcess.StandardInput.WriteAsync(line);
        await searchTableProcess.StandardInput.FlushAsync();
    }
    await searchTableProcess.StandardInput.FlushAsync();
    Console.WriteLine("done writing");
});

for (int index = 0; index < hashes.Count; index++)
{
    string curLine = await searchTableProcess.StandardOutput.ReadLineAsync();
    // do work

    Console.WriteLine(index + 1);
}
```

Note that I have tested the child program independently and it works well on a console. It is a native C++ program compiled with MSVC and uses `fgets` and `printf` to read and write respectively.

The problem is that the output read by `searchTableProcess.StandardOutput` seems to be buffered internally by .NET Core. So even while I write input to `StandardInput` one line at a time, the output comes out in chunks like this:

Lines 1-80 displayed
\<long pause\>
Lines 81-144 displayed
\<long pause\>
Lines 145-211 displayed
\<long pause\>
Lines 212-252 displayed
\<hangs indefinitely\>

It seems obvious that this is due to buffering at some level. But there is a bigger issue - when I have written all 300 lines to `StandardInput`, the final few lines of the output don't even show up in `StandardOutput` i.e. `ReadLineAsync` hangs indefinitely waiting for the last 50 lines or so. I believe this is because the aforementioned buffer isn't full yet and it doesn't get flushed.

I tested this theory by sending bogus lines after the original 300 and then killing the process after the 300 I need are printed. This works fine.

It seems to be an issue with .NET Core since it works fine on console. Please let me know if you require more information.

